            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the Trophic State Index (TSI)?</h2>
              <p>
                The <strong>Trophic State Index (TSI)</strong> is a numerical
                scale used to describe the nutrient status and productivity of
                lakes and reservoirs. The most widely used version is
                <strong>Carlson’s TSI</strong>, which converts common water
                quality measurements into a 0–100 scale:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Low TSI</strong> → clear, nutrient‑poor,
                  low‑productivity lakes (oligotrophic).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>High TSI</strong> → nutrient‑rich, algae‑dominated
                  lakes (eutrophic or hypereutrophic).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator implements Carlson’s original equations for:
                <strong>Secchi depth (SD)</strong>,
                <strong>chlorophyll‑a (CHL)</strong>, and
                <strong>total phosphorus (TP)</strong>, and then summarizes them
                into an average TSI and trophic class.
              </p>

              <h2>Carlson TSI formulas used in this calculator</h2>
              <p>
                All logarithms are base‑10. Units must match the equations
                below.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  1. TSI from Secchi depth (SD, meters)
                </p>
                <p>Secchi depth is first converted to meters if needed.</p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  TSI(SD) = 60 − 14.41 × log<sub>10</sub>(SD)
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  2. TSI from chlorophyll‑a (CHL, µg/L)
                </p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  TSI(CHL) = 9.81 × log<sub>10</sub>(CHL) + 30.6
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  3. TSI from total phosphorus (TP, µg/L)
                </p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  TSI(TP) = 14.42 × log<sub>10</sub>(TP) + 4.15
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">4. Average TSI</p>
                <p>
                  If more than one parameter is provided, the calculator reports
                  the
                  <strong>arithmetic mean</strong> of all available TSI values:
                </p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  TSI<sub>avg</sub> = (TSI(SD) + TSI(CHL) + TSI(TP)) / N
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                  where <em>N</em> is the number of valid TSI values (1–3).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How to interpret TSI values</h2>
              <p>
                There is no single universal classification, but the following
                ranges are widely used for Carlson’s TSI:
              </p>

              <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                <thead>
                  <tr class="bg-gray-100">
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      TSI range
                    </th>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Trophic class
                    </th>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Typical characteristics
                    </th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">&lt; 40</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 font-semibold">
                      Oligotrophic
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Very clear water, low nutrients, low algal biomass, often
                      deep and cold lakes with high oxygen in bottom waters.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">40 – 50</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 font-semibold">
                      Mesotrophic
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Moderate nutrients and productivity, occasional algal
                      blooms, generally good recreational quality.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">50 – 70</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 font-semibold">
                      Eutrophic
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      High nutrients, frequent or persistent algal blooms,
                      reduced water clarity, possible oxygen depletion in bottom
                      waters.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">&gt; 70</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 font-semibold">
                      Hypereutrophic
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Very high nutrients and algal biomass, poor water clarity,
                      frequent nuisance or harmful algal blooms, strong oxygen
                      depletion risk.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>

              <h2>
                Reading differences between TSI(SD), TSI(CHL), and TSI(TP)
              </h2>
              <p>
                One strength of Carlson’s approach is that
                <strong>disagreement</strong> between the three TSI values can
                reveal important lake processes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>TSI(SD) &gt; TSI(CHL)</strong> (Secchi indicates more
                  eutrophic than chlorophyll):<br />
                  Water clarity is worse than expected from algae alone.
                  Possible causes include non‑algal turbidity (suspended
                  sediments, colored dissolved organic matter).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>TSI(SD) &lt; TSI(CHL)</strong> (Secchi indicates more
                  oligotrophic than chlorophyll):<br />
                  Water is clearer than expected for the measured chlorophyll.
                  This can occur in lakes with large zooplankton grazing,
                  macrophyte dominance, or strong stratification.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>TSI(TP) &gt; TSI(CHL)</strong>:<br />
                  Phosphorus is relatively high compared with algal biomass.
                  Nutrients may be tied up in sediments, macrophytes, or another
                  factor (e.g., light, nitrogen, grazing) is limiting algal
                  growth.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>TSI(TP) &lt; TSI(CHL)</strong>:<br />
                  Chlorophyll is high relative to phosphorus. Possible
                  explanations include internal loading, nitrogen limitation, or
                  sampling during/after a bloom event.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The “Consistency among indicators” note in the calculator
                summarizes these patterns to support quick interpretation.
              </p>

              <h2>Step‑by‑step: using the TSI calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Collect measurements</strong><br />
                  Use standard field and lab protocols to measure:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Secchi depth (m or ft) with a Secchi disk.</li>
                    <li>Chlorophyll‑a (µg/L) from water samples.</li>
                    <li>Total phosphorus (µg/L) from water samples.</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter your data</strong><br />
                  Type each value into the corresponding field. You can enter
                  one, two, or all three parameters.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Run the calculation</strong><br />
                  Click <em>“Calculate TSI”</em>. The tool:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Converts Secchi depth to meters if needed.</li>
                    <li>
                      Computes TSI(SD), TSI(CHL), and TSI(TP) using Carlson’s
                      equations.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Calculates the average TSI from all available indicators.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Assigns a trophic class and provides a short
                      interpretation.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interpret and compare</strong><br />
                  Use the TSI table above and the consistency note to understand
                  whether your lake is nutrient‑poor, moderate, or
                  nutrient‑rich, and whether non‑algal factors may be affecting
                  water clarity.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Limitations and good practice</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>TSI is a screening tool</strong>, not a full
                  ecological assessment. It focuses on nutrients and algal
                  biomass, not toxicity, pathogens, or habitat.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use consistent methods</strong> for Secchi,
                  chlorophyll‑a, and phosphorus to compare sites or years.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider seasonality</strong>: TSI can vary strongly
                  over the growing season. Many monitoring programs use
                  mid‑summer averages.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Combine with other indicators</strong> such as
                  dissolved oxygen profiles, nitrogen, and biological
                  assessments for management decisions.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is there a “good” TSI value?</h3>
              <p>
                It depends on management goals. Oligotrophic lakes (low TSI) are
                often valued for drinking water and recreation, while moderately
                productive mesotrophic lakes can support good fisheries. Very
                high TSI values (eutrophic–hypereutrophic) are usually
                associated with nuisance blooms and degraded water quality.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I compare TSI between different lakes?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, as long as measurements are collected with comparable
                methods and at similar times of year. TSI is widely used to
                compare lakes within a region or track changes over time in a
                single lake.
              </p>

              <h3>What if I only have Secchi depth?</h3>
              <p>
                You can still compute TSI(SD) and get a rough trophic
                classification. Adding chlorophyll‑a and phosphorus improves
                diagnostic power and helps distinguish between algal and
                non‑algal drivers of water clarity.
              </p>
            </section>
